# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ib-governor — environment secrets
#
# These are SECRETS and stay out of git. Copy this file to `.env` (gitignored)
# and fill in the two values below:
#
#     cp .env.example .env
#
# You only need these to RUN/ARM the live daemon — so it can push Telegram alerts
# and accept your `CONFIRM <token>` replies. The test suite does NOT need them.
#
# NOTE: IBKR connection settings (host / port / client_id) are NOT here — they
# live in config/rules.yaml under `live:` (they're config, not secrets).
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN — the API token for YOUR Telegram bot.
# How to get it:
#   1. In Telegram, open a chat with @BotFather (the official bot that makes bots).
#   2. Send /newbot and follow the prompts: pick a display name, then a username
#      that ends in "bot" (e.g. my_ibgov_bot).
#   3. BotFather replies with a token like  123456789:AAH9x...Qw  — paste it below.
#   (Lost it later? Send /token to @BotFather to view or regenerate.)
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=

# TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID — the numeric id of the chat the daemon messages (you).
# A bot cannot message you until you have messaged it first, so:
#   1. Open a chat with the bot you just created and send it any message (e.g. "hi").
#   2. Get your id either way:
#        • Easiest: message @userinfobot — it replies with your numeric "Id".
#        • Or open this URL in a browser (paste your token in for <TOKEN>):
#            https://api.telegram.org/bot<TOKEN>/getUpdates
#          and read the number at  result[0].message.chat.id
#   3. Paste that number below. (Personal chats are positive; group ids are negative.)
TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID=
